30
00:02:57,650 --> 00:03:04,150
understanding of human thought and behavior.
We'll explore several examples of this in

31
00:03:04,150 --> 00:03:10,060
the lectures later this week, but let's take
a brief look at an example now. I'd like you

32
00:03:10,060 --> 00:03:17,060
to ask yourself how you would regard the prospect
of betting in each of three tennis matches.

33
00:03:17,680 --> 00:03:23,019
In Match 1, you know everything about players
A and B, and you know that their win-lose

34
00:03:23,019 --> 00:03:28,680
record against each other is exactly 50-50.
Both are healthy and in good form for this

35
00:03:28,680 --> 00:03:34,879
match. You could very reasonably regard Players
A and B as each having a probability of 1/2

36
00:03:34,879 --> 00:03:39,860
of winning this match.
In Match 2, you know nothing about players

37
00:03:39,860 --> 00:03:44,549
C and D, and nothing about their appearance
before the match tells you which one is the

38
00:03:44,549 --> 00:03:49,840
better player. You could very reasonably regard
Players C and D as each having a probability

39
00:03:49,840 --> 00:03:56,840
of anywhere from 0 to 1 of winning this match.
In Match 3, you also know nothing about players

40
00:03:58,549 --> 00:04:04,280
E and F, but a good friend of yours who knows a lot
about them starts to tell you about the match.

41
00:04:04,280 --> 00:04:09,750
He says that one player is much better than
the other, and is certain to win the match.

42
00:04:09,750 --> 00:04:12,950
But your friend is distracted and removed
from you before he can tell you which player

43
00:04:12,950 --> 00:04:19,950
it is. You could very reasonably regard Players
E and F as each having a probability of either

44
00:04:19,969 --> 00:04:26,969
nearly 0 or nearly 1 of winning this match.
